{  
  "response_text": "The cumulative number of livestock destocked starts at zero and increases gradually from the initial steps. This rise likely reflects adaptation to stochastic rainfall variability (mean = 200, std = 100), which periodically reduces pasture biomass, triggering destocking when biomass falls below the satisficing threshold (set to zero). The average trend peaks midway through the simulation, mirroring increased destocking during prolonged dry years exacerbated by cumulative livestock pressure. Post-peak, a plateau emerges as households balance reduced stocking levels with rainfall recovery, stabilizing the total near ~120 units. Variance across runs grows after the first 20 steps, indicating heightened sensitivity to rare, low-rainfall events and localized resource depletion. Deviation patterns align with climate-driven shocks, suggesting households retain conservative stocking tactics under risk-averse attitudes (risk-att-init = 0.5). Destocking trajectories lack abrupt shifts due to absent social learning mechanisms (homog-behav-types?) and static strategic behaviors (no strategy-switching). The mean line’s exponential-like increase followed by concavity parallels drought-recovery cycles, with destocking intensity proportional to persistent deficit periods exceeding 5–10 consecutive low-rainfall years."  
}

